			<h2 class="comments-title">
			7 replies to &ldquo;<span>It&#039;s Still OK to Hate the Government</span>&rdquo;		</h2>

		<ol class="commentlist">
				<li class="comment even thread-even depth-1" id="li-comment-19">
		<article id="comment-19" class="comment">
			<header class="comment-meta comment-author vcard">
				<img alt='' src='http://1.gravatar.com/avatar/775a5858a9eff1adcdd60e2d06083e04?s=44&amp;d=identicon&amp;r=G' class='avatar avatar-44 photo' height='44' width='44' /><cite><b class="fn"><a href='http://sophistpundit.blogspot.com' rel='external nofollow' class='url'>Adam</a></b> </cite><a href="http://elidourado.com/blog/ok-to-hate-the-government/#comment-19"><time datetime="2010-01-19T11:08:58+00:00">January 19, 2010 at 11:08 am</time></a>			</header><!-- .comment-meta -->

			
			<section class="comment-content comment">
				<p>I of course agree with most of what you say here, except in characterizing the actions of the Founding Fathers as attempting to constrain the state by writing down rules, or calling them an abject failure.</p>
<p>I don&#8217;t think that the Constitution was simply an attempt to chain the state with the written word; I think it was written as a contract between the many states that considered themselves sovereign in their own right, as to the terms they were willing to give up some sovereignty to a government that would preside over all of them.  A lot of the things that it gets made fun of for&#8211;like the 3/5 clause&#8211;are misunderstood because they&#8217;re viewed from the perspective of universal rights, when in fact they were simply <i>comprimises</i> between the interests of the different states involved.</p>
<p>Moreover, I don&#8217;t think it&#8217;s really fair to call what they did an &#8220;abject failure&#8221;.  The question becomes: in comparison to what?</p>
							</section><!-- .comment-content -->

			<div class="reply">
							</div><!-- .reply -->
		</article><!-- #comment-## -->
	</li><!-- #comment-## -->
	<li class="comment byuser comment-author-elidourado bypostauthor odd alt thread-odd thread-alt depth-1" id="li-comment-20">
		<article id="comment-20" class="comment">
			<header class="comment-meta comment-author vcard">
				<img alt='' src='http://0.gravatar.com/avatar/89e73bc0be13bb5a395a4140290ee177?s=44&amp;d=identicon&amp;r=G' class='avatar avatar-44 photo' height='44' width='44' /><cite><b class="fn"><a href='http://elidourado.com/' rel='external nofollow' class='url'>Eli</a></b> <span>Post author</span></cite><a href="http://elidourado.com/blog/ok-to-hate-the-government/#comment-20"><time datetime="2010-01-19T11:22:20+00:00">January 19, 2010 at 11:22 am</time></a>			</header><!-- .comment-meta -->

			
			<section class="comment-content comment">
				<p>Adam, I prefer my interpretation, but even on your own terms, viewing the Constitution as a contract between the states, I don&#8217;t see how it is possible to regard the Founding Fathers as successful if the contract is not today being enforced in the way it was written.</p>
<p>In terms of comparison, pick your poison: comparison to what they expected to achieve, to the Articles of Confederation, or to simply not forming a political union in the first place.</p>
							</section><!-- .comment-content -->

