			<header class="comment-meta comment-author vcard">
				<img alt='' src='http://1.gravatar.com/avatar/775a5858a9eff1adcdd60e2d06083e04?s=44&amp;d=identicon&amp;r=G' class='avatar avatar-44 photo' height='44' width='44' /><cite><b class="fn"><a href='http://sophistpundit.blogspot.com' rel='external nofollow' class='url'>Adam</a></b> </cite><a href="http://elidourado.com/blog/ok-to-hate-the-government/#comment-21"><time datetime="2010-01-19T12:23:21+00:00">January 19, 2010 at 12:23 pm</time></a>			</header><!-- .comment-meta -->

			
			<section class="comment-content comment">
				<p>Those are not the points of comparison that I&#8217;d pick.  I&#8217;d pick other countries, particularly ones, like Columbia, that have attempted similar &#8220;constitution&#8221; strategies.</p>
							</section><!-- .comment-content -->

			<div class="reply">
							</div><!-- .reply -->
		</article><!-- #comment-## -->
	</li><!-- #comment-## -->
	<li class="comment odd alt thread-odd thread-alt depth-1" id="li-comment-22">
		<article id="comment-22" class="comment">
			<header class="comment-meta comment-author vcard">
				<img alt='' src='http://1.gravatar.com/avatar/1640a196d9b2949802752f59c2144880?s=44&amp;d=identicon&amp;r=G' class='avatar avatar-44 photo' height='44' width='44' /><cite><b class="fn"><a href='http://overtonsarrow.wordpress.com' rel='external nofollow' class='url'>Carl Oberg</a></b> </cite><a href="http://elidourado.com/blog/ok-to-hate-the-government/#comment-22"><time datetime="2010-01-19T12:43:29+00:00">January 19, 2010 at 12:43 pm</time></a>			</header><!-- .comment-meta -->

			
			<section class="comment-content comment">
				<p>Thanks, Eli, for posting this.  It definitely needs to be discussed.</p>
<p>First, they shouldn&#8217;t have used words like &#8220;love&#8221;, &#8220;hate&#8221; etc.  Would this conversation even be happening if they had used words like &#8220;understand&#8221;?</p>
<p>Second, I appreciate your list of self-executing reforms and for the most part agree.  But the current political climate plus the snowballed effect of 200+ years of a &#8220;failed&#8221; constitution render such radical, libertarian solutions dead on arrival.</p>
<p>I&#8217;ll be first in line advocating for the abolition of all drug laws, but if forced to wager how drug freedom would come about, I would put my money on some sort of state-level regulatory solution like state-run alcohol stores.  That just seems like the more likely (but not optimal) solution.  It&#8217;s not that these solutions are not self-executing &#8230; it&#8217;s that the self-executing solution is not at all likely.  As you say, it&#8217;s the institutional environment.  Which I proudly hate.</p>
<p>So doesn&#8217;t this all come down to whether or not you are willing to play in the hated institutional swamp governed by a failed, misinterpreted document?  You, I surmise, are not.  I, on the other hand, find comfort in standing athwart institutional inevitability.</p>
							</section><!-- .comment-content -->

			<div class="reply">
							</div><!-- .reply -->
		</article><!-- #comment-## -->
	</li><!-- #comment-## -->
	<li class="comment byuser comment-author-elidourado bypostauthor even thread-even depth-1" id="li-comment-23">
		<article id="comment-23" class="comment">
			<header class="comment-meta comment-author vcard">
				<img alt='' src='http://0.gravatar.com/avatar/89e73bc0be13bb5a395a4140290ee177?s=44&amp;d=identicon&amp;r=G' class='avatar avatar-44 photo' height='44' width='44' /><cite><b class="fn"><a href='http://elidourado.com/' rel='external nofollow' class='url'>Eli</a></b> <span>Post author</span></cite><a href="http://elidourado.com/blog/ok-to-hate-the-government/#comment-23"><time datetime="2010-01-19T13:01:41+00:00">January 19, 2010 at 1:01 pm</time></a>			</header><!-- .comment-meta -->

			
			<section class="comment-content comment">
				<p>Adam, that&#8217;s not a reasonable comparison because Colombia does not have the same or even similar non-governmental institutions.</p>
<p>But in any case, I think we can agree that written constitutions tend to be eroded over time for public choice reasons and that it is best not to naïvely downplay such concerns, which was the point I was trying to convey in the first place.</p>
							</section><!-- .comment-content -->

			<div class="reply">
							</div><!-- .reply -->
		</article><!-- #comment-## -->
	</li><!-- #comment-## -->
	<li class="comment byuser comment-author-elidourado bypostauthor odd alt thread-odd thread-alt depth-1" id="li-comment-24">
		<article id="comment-24" class="comment">
			<header class="comment-meta comment-author vcard">
				<img alt='' src='http://0.gravatar.com/avatar/89e73bc0be13bb5a395a4140290ee177?s=44&amp;d=identicon&amp;r=G' class='avatar avatar-44 photo' height='44' width='44' /><cite><b class="fn"><a href='http://elidourado.com/' rel='external nofollow' class='url'>Eli</a></b> <span>Post author</span></cite><a href="http://elidourado.com/blog/ok-to-hate-the-government/#comment-24"><time datetime="2010-01-19T13:41:59+00:00">January 19, 2010 at 1:41 pm</time></a>			</header><!-- .comment-meta -->

			
			<section class="comment-content comment">
				<p>Carl, thanks for your distillation of the issue. I agree that self-executing solutions that will never be tried are irrelevant. Nevertheless, I think most (not all) plausible libertarian reforms, even if botched, are likely to make people better off rather than worse off. For example, if states start to run marijuana stores, even if they do a bad job at it somehow, it would be better than prohibition. In this sense, most reforms are not at all like the attempted deregulation of energy markets in California.</p>
<p>It is certainly better to have well-executed reforms than poorly-executed reforms, and I am glad there are libertarians, like you, who work within the system to make it better. But whether one is willing to play in the institutional swamp is, as you suggest, a matter of personal preference. The claim, made by Eggers and O&#8217;Leary, that those who do not wish to do so are &#8220;misguided&#8221;, or have a &#8220;blind spot,&#8221; is unsupported, and I think it is quite reasonable for those who wish to be reflexive government-bashers to pursue their happiness in that manner.</p>
							</section><!-- .comment-content -->

			<div class="reply">
							</div><!-- .reply -->
		</article><!-- #comment-## -->
